, the study probes the objectives of the president and other framers of new policies and programs, within the institutional and political context of the time. The authors give special attention to the inherent incongruities that arise when intergovernmental programs are used to address problems defined in national terms. In addition, they reveal how certain programs actually challenged the power of established national bureaucracies. They conclude with a thoughtful overview of the Johnson legacy in intergovernmental relations during subsequent administrations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aEconomic assistance, DomesticzUnited States. 0aIntergovernmental fiscal relationszUnited States. 0aUnited States--Politics and government--1963-1969. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Affairs & Administration.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, James E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurkhead, Jesse, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRedford, Emmette S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWelborn, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477303450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477303450/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK